---
import BlogLayout from '../../layouts/BlogLayout.astro';
const faqs = [
  { q: 'What does duplicating words look like?', a: '"hello world" becomes "hello hello world world" (with a space separator).' },
  { q: 'Can I change the separator between duplicated words?', a: 'Yes — choose space, comma, hyphen, or slash between the original and its copy.' },
  { q: 'Does it duplicate every single word?', a: 'Yes — every non-whitespace token is duplicated. Blank lines are passed through unchanged.' },
];
---
<BlogLayout
  title="How to Duplicate Words in Text Online Free — Word Doubler"
  description="Make every word appear twice in text. Choose the separator between copies. Free online word duplicator tool."
  canonical="/blog/how-to-duplicate-words-in-text-online-free"
  date="2026-07-03"
  readTime="2 min read"
  category="Text Utilities"
  faqs={faqs}
>
  <p>The word duplicator repeats every word in your text immediately after itself — "the quick fox" becomes "the the quick quick fox fox". Useful for stutter effects, emphasis, and testing text-processing pipelines.</p>

  <h2>How to Duplicate Words</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>Paste your text into the input box.</li>
    <li>Choose the separator between copies (space, comma, hyphen, or slash).</li>
    <li>Copy the result.</li>
  </ol>

  <div class="my-8 p-5 bg-violet-950/40 border border-violet-800/50 rounded-2xl text-center">
    <p class="text-slate-300 mb-3">Double every word in text — free, instant</p>
    <a href="/tools/duplicate-words" class="inline-block bg-violet-600 hover:bg-violet-500 text-white font-semibold px-6 py-3 rounded-xl transition-colors">Open Duplicate Words Tool →</a>
  </div>
</BlogLayout>
